<subSubSection id="19ED87905F63A901FF40D29E283CFC5A" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="257" pageId="9" pageNumber="256" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="5148D41B5F63A901FF40D29E2B1BFF56" blockId="9.[136,1452,1860,2067]" lastBlockId="10.[136,1452,158,976]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="257" pageId="9" pageNumber="256">
<emphasis id="638308095F63A902FF40D29E2814F840" bold="true" box="[189,335,1968,1994]" pageId="9" pageNumber="256">Distribution</emphasis>
:— 
<collectingRegion id="93331AF95F63A902FE8CD29E2B6DF840" box="[369,566,1968,1994]" country="India" name="Madhya Pradesh" pageId="9" pageNumber="256">Madhya Pradesh</collectingRegion>
: Burhanpur, Ratlam and Jhabua districts; 
<collectingRegion id="93331AF95F63A902FBEAD29E2D2BF840" box="[1047,1136,1968,1994]" country="India" name="Gujarat" pageId="9" pageNumber="256">Gujarat</collectingRegion>
: Rajkot district, Saurashtra, Peninsular 
<collectingCountry id="29E0948B5F63A902FEF7D2FA281CF864" box="[266,327,2004,2030]" name="India" pageId="9" pageNumber="256">India</collectingCountry>
. According to one of the collectors, Dr. Mujaffar Shaikh, this species is seen in a considerable abundance in open grassland in 
<quantity id="960F79FE5F63A902FE01D2D72B63F798" box="[508,568,2040,2067]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="256" unit="km" value="7.0">7 km</quantity>
<superScript id="A68279535F63A902FDC5D2D62B1BF78C" attach="left" box="[568,576,2040,2054]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="256">2</superScript>
of area in Asiragarh forest range, Burhanpur district of 
<collectingRegion id="93331AF95F63A902FB36D2D62CD6F798" box="[1227,1421,2040,2066]" country="India" name="Madhya Pradesh" pageId="9" pageNumber="256">Madhya Pradesh</collectingRegion>
. A species occurring in such profusion yet remained to be un-described for centuries is fascinating. The species so far appears to be endemic to Central 
<collectingCountry id="29E0948B5F60A901FE02D5EC2B67FF56" box="[511,572,194,220]" name="India" pageId="10" pageNumber="257">India</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5148D41B5F60A901FF40D5C82C13FD3B" blockId="10.[136,1452,158,976]" pageId="10" pageNumber="257">
<emphasis id="638308095F60A901FF40D5C8285BFE8A" bold="true" box="[189,256,230,256]" pageId="10" pageNumber="257">Notes</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName id="96F7AF985F60A901FED9D5C82B16FE8A" authorityName="A. P. Tiwari &amp; Chorghe" authorityYear="2020" box="[292,589,230,256]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Parahyparrhenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="257" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="khannae">
<emphasis id="638308095F60A901FED9D5C82B16FE8A" box="[292,589,230,256]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="257">Parahyparrhenia khannae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a very slender grass with an ascending habit (
<figureCitation id="C9CCC89E5F60A901FB8AD5C82DE1FE8A" box="[1143,1210,230,256]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[136,229,2046,2068]" captionTargetBox="[302,1285,314,2018]" captionTargetId="figure-53@7.[302,1285,314,2018]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Habit of Parahyparrhenia khannae. (Based on A.P. Tiwari 75590: holotype)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392632" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392632/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="257">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) and has the shortest stature (ca. 
<quantity id="960F79FE5F60A901FEF4D4242816FEAF" box="[265,333,266,293]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="257" unit="cm" value="30.0">30 cm</quantity>
high) and smallest anther size (i.e. 
<quantity id="960F79FE5F60A901FD2AD4242A06FEAF" box="[727,861,266,293]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="257" unit="mm" value="0.65" valueMax="0.8" valueMin="0.5">0.5–0.8 mm</quantity>
long) known in the genus. The racemes are terminal, solitary in 2–3 pedunculate fascicles, extremely narrow with considerably long awns i.e. ca. 
<quantity id="960F79FE5F60A901FB5ED4002DABFEC3" box="[1187,1264,302,329]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.3" pageId="10" pageNumber="257" unit="cm" value="6.3">6.3 cm</quantity>
long, giving the plant a peculiar appearance at a glance. The obliquely pungent and protruded callus in this species is a very prominent feature which is capable of driving into the finger, if pressed against it. When mature, the lower glume of the sessile spikelet becomes highly coriaceous, darkened and tough, enclosing the caryopsis very tightly. As the lower glume of the sessile spikelet is longitudinally grooved on its dorsal side, it bears a prominent ridge on its ventral surface, which is the cause of the longitudinal depression on the matured caryopsis (
<figureCitation id="C9CCC89E5F60A901FC26D4CC2D44FE76" box="[987,1055,482,508]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="9.[136,229,1683,1705]" captionTargetBox="[340,1247,713,1659]" captionTargetId="figure-254@9.[340,1247,713,1659]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 4. Habit and parts of the spikelets of Parahyparrhenia khannae. A. Habit. B. Spiciform-raceme. C. Ligule. D. A pair of heterogamous spikelets. E. Pedicel with oblique apex. F. Upper lemma of the sessile spikelet. G. Lower glume of the sessile spikelet.H. Pistil. I. Stamens. J. Pedicelled spikelet without a pedicel. K. Lower glume of the pedicelled spikelet. L. Caryopsis. (Photography by: Mujaffar Shaikh)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392638" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392638/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="257">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
, L). The mature hardened spikelets of this species render the task of manually removing the caryopsis, without completely destroying the glume, very formidable. The leaf blades are granulated on their abaxial surface/under-surface; one of the distinguishing features of this species. The raceme and spikelets are much narrower as compared to 
<taxonomicName id="96F7AF985F60A901FC2FD7612D2AFDE2" authorityName="Clayton" authorityYear="1972" baseAuthorityName="Hackel" baseAuthorityYear="1885" box="[978,1137,590,616]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Parahyparrhenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="257" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bellariensis">
<emphasis id="638308095F60A901FC2FD7612D2AFDE2" box="[978,1137,590,616]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="257">P. bellariensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In both the Indian species, lobes of the upper lemma of the sessile spikelet can be best seen during anthesis; later, at maturity, the lobes tend to disintegrate making the lemma appear absolutely entire or undivided like 
<taxonomicName id="96F7AF985F60A901FC3FD7B92C18FD3B" authority="Persoon (1807: 533)" authorityName="Persoon" authorityPageNumber="533" authorityYear="1807" box="[962,1347,662,689]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Heteropogon" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="257" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="638308095F60A901FC3FD7B92D0EFD3A" box="[962,1109,663,688]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="257">Heteropogon</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="3566A9EA5F60A901FBA1D7B92C18FD3B" author="Persoon, C. H." box="[1116,1347,662,689]" pageId="10" pageNumber="257" refId="ref9630" refString="Persoon, C. H. (1807) Synopsis plantarum: seu enchiridium botanicum, complectens enumerationem systematicam specierum hucusque cognitarum. Pars II. Apud Bibliopolas, Treuttel et Wurtz, Parisiis Lutetiorum, 533 pp." type="book" year="1807">Persoon (1807: 533)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5148D41B5F60A901FF40D7942DF1FD72" blockId="10.[136,1452,158,976]" pageId="10" pageNumber="257">
So far, this species is known from 
<collectingRegion id="93331AF95F60A901FDC3D7942AD8FD5E" box="[574,899,698,724]" isEnumeration="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="257">Madhya Pradesh and Gujarat</collectingRegion>
states. Based on its habitats specificity, it may be predicted that it is likely to occur in dry grasslands of Northern 
<collectingRegion id="93331AF95F60A901FCADD7F02DFDFD72" box="[848,1190,734,760]" isEnumeration="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="257">Maharashtra and Chhattisgarh</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
